## Pre-edit gate (NON-NEGOTIABLE)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Before writing or editing any rule with `action = "skip"`, complete steps 1-3 below. Skipping this gate is a critical review finding.

1. **Read the Cloudflare authoritative docs (do not rely on training-data memory):**
   - [Add an exception via API](https://developers.cloudflare.com/waf/managed-rules/waf-exceptions/define-api/) - confirms `action: skip`, `action_parameters` shape, and the must-be-positioned-before-execute-rule rule.
   - [Create an exception (Ruleset Engine)](https://developers.cloudflare.com/ruleset-engine/managed-rulesets/create-exception/) - the four exception types (`ruleset: current`, `rulesets: [...]`, `rules: { id: [...] }`).
   - [WAF Managed Rules configuration using Terraform](https://developers.cloudflare.com/terraform/additional-configurations/waf-managed-rulesets/) - canonical Terraform shape.
   - [Ruleset Engine fields reference](https://developers.cloudflare.com/ruleset-engine/rules-language/fields/) - confirm exact field names (`http.request.uri.path`, `http.request.headers["..."][*]`, `ip.src`, etc.).
   - When the exception involves attack patterns (multipart, JSON, etc.), also read the relevant [OWASP Managed Ruleset](https://developers.cloudflare.com/waf/managed-rules/reference/owasp-core-ruleset/) reference for the rule IDs being skipped.
   - Note any change to the API or Terraform provider since the rules in this file were last touched (use the [WAF changelog](https://developers.cloudflare.com/waf/change-log/) and [Cloudflare Terraform changelog](https://github.com/cloudflare/terraform-provider-cloudflare/blob/master/CHANGELOG.md)).
   - If the workspace has the `user-cloudflare-docs` MCP server configured, prefer that for fresh fetches over training-data memory.

2. **Survey the peer rules in the same zone.** The closest existing rule to your use case is your reference shape. Mirror it line-for-line; do not invent a new pattern unless the case genuinely demands it (and document why in your provenance artifact). Use the carrier appropriate to your interface: in Terraform, scan the rules in the same `.tf` file; in Dashboard, scan the rules listed for the phase + zone in the UI; in API, `GET` the current ruleset JSON and grep it.

   ### Canonical shapes for managed-rule exceptions (skip rules)

   | Pattern (purpose-based name) | Predicate shape | Use when |
   |---|---|---|
   | `<app>-stcore-upload-file-skip` | host (set) + method `PUT` + `ip.src in $trusted_egress_ips` + path prefix + multipart content-type + `filename=` body | Streamlit / file-uploader endpoints, multipart PUT, internal users |
   | `<app>-workbook-upload-skip` | host eq + method `POST` + (geo OR trusted) + path eq + multipart content-type + `filename=` body | Specific endpoint, browser POST, mixed-internet users |
   | `<app>-file-upload-browser-skip` | host eq + method `POST` + path eq + multipart content-type + `filename=` body + `origin` header eq + `corp_egress_ips` | Specific browser endpoint, browser-only path requires origin pinning |
   | `<app>-api-multipart-skip` | host eq + method `POST` + path prefix + multipart content-type + `filename=` body | API-shaped multipart uploads, no browser context |
   | `<app>-dashboard-be-post-skip` | host eq + method `POST` + path prefix (broad API) | Server-to-server endpoint, no body inspection needed |

   ### Canonical shapes for custom rules

   | Pattern family | Shape | Use when |
   |---|---|---|
   | `block-non-trusted-egress-ips` family | `block` action + host + path scope + `not (ip.src in $trusted_egress_ips)` | Internal-only endpoint must be reachable only from trusted egress |
   | `allow-us-only-and-trusted` family | `skip` action with high-priority allow + `(ip.geoip.country eq "US" or ip.src in $trusted_egress_ips)` + host scope | Geo-restricted public-ish endpoint |
   | `allow-<region>-and-trusted` (e.g., US+CA, TW) | Same as above with extra country + trusted-IPs escape hatch | Targeted regional rollouts; always add trusted IPs as escape hatch |
   | `geo-block-OFAC` (continent or country list) | `block` action + `ip.geoip.country in {"CU" "IR" "KP" "RU" "SY"}` | OFAC sanctioned countries; never user-configurable, always block |
   | `attack-score-gate` (Enterprise) | `cf.waf.score le N` scoped to host/path | Sensitive paths; supplements managed rules, doesn't replace them |

   For new custom rules: prefer **allow before block** (skip-allow rule positioned above the block rule) so the trusted-egress escape hatch always wins ties.

3. **Confirm the request actually requires a skip.** Validate from the requester:
   - Ticket / change number, owner, business justification
   - The exact host(s), path(s), method(s), expected request shape
   - Whether the legitimate flow originates in a browser app (origin header pinning available) or server-to-server (it isn't)
   - Whether the legitimate flow's source IPs are knowable (trusted egress, named source set) or fully open (geo at most)
   - Which OWASP child-rule IDs are actually firing on the legitimate flow (from Security Events). Skip only those, not the whole ruleset.

If any of the above is missing, **stop and ask** before drafting the rule. Do not invent guards or scope.

