## Required guards - Managed-Rule Exceptions (action = skip)

Every skip rule MUST include the guards in its row, plus the standard host + method.

| Exception type | Required guards (in addition to host + method) |
|---|---|
| **Multipart file upload** | `any(lower(http.request.headers["content-type"][*])[*] contains "multipart/form-data")` AND `http.request.body.raw contains "filename="` AND scoped source (trusted IPs, geo, or origin header) |
| **Browser-app POST (specific endpoint)** | `any(http.request.headers["origin"][*] eq "https://<browser-app-host>")` AND scoped source (trusted IPs or geo) |
| **Server-to-server POST** | scoped source (trusted IPs OR a named ASN / IP set). Origin header guard is meaningless here - do not use. |
| **Streamlit / file-uploader endpoint** | path prefix with trailing slash + multipart guards above. Streamlit uses `/_stcore/upload_file/<uuid>`. |
| **Geo-only allow** | `(ip.geoip.continent in {"NA"} or ip.src in $trusted_egress_ips)` style - never bare geo without trusted-IPs escape hatch. |

## Required guards - Custom Rules (action = block / challenge / etc.)

| Custom rule type | Required guards |
|---|---|
| **Geo allowlist (block-by-default)** | Country / continent predicate AND trusted-egress escape hatch (`ip.src in $trusted_egress_ips`). Never block based purely on geo - internal users travel. |
| **OFAC / sanctioned-country block** | `ip.geoip.country in {"CU" "IR" "KP" "RU" "SY"}` (literal list, never variable). No escape hatch - this is a compliance block, not a policy choice. |
| **Endpoint allowlist (specific path → specific source)** | host eq + path predicate (eq / starts_with per matrix) + source predicate (trusted IPs, named source set, or geo). Use `skip` action positioned above the deny rule. |
| **Attack-score gate (Enterprise plan)** | host + path scope + `cf.waf.score le N` (per `400-cloudflare.mdc` § "WAF Attack Score (Plan-Aware)"). Never gate globally on raw score; always combine with host / path / method. |
| **Bot / ASN block** | `ip.geoip.asnum in {<list>}` OR `cf.client.bot` predicate. Document the ASN owner and the incident that justified the block. |

### Why each guard exists (cite this in your inline comment)

- **`lower(...)` + `any(...)` content-type normalization** - request `content-type` is a multi-value header (`headers["content-type"][*]`). `any(...)[*] contains "multipart/form-data"` matches any value, lowercased, which handles `Multipart/Form-Data`, `multipart/form-data; boundary=...`, etc. This is the canonical form. Inventing a single-value `eq` check is wrong.
- **`filename=` body marker** - narrows the skip to actual file uploads, rejects POSTs with multipart content-type but no file part. Cheap, unambiguous, defends against tooling that mis-sets content-type.
- **`origin` header bracket + wildcard + `eq`** - `any(http.request.headers["origin"][*] eq "https://...")`. The `[*]` wildcard handles missing-or-multi-valued origin (browser sends one; some tooling sends none or multiple). Plain `http.request.headers["origin"] eq "..."` is wrong syntax - it's a multi-value field. Pinning to the browser app's own origin defeats forged-content-type server-to-server POSTs riding the skip.
- **`ip.src in $trusted_egress_ips`** - the named list is maintained centrally. Hardcoding IPs is forbidden - use the list reference.
- **OWASP child-rule list (the multipart baseline)** - shared by every multipart upload skip in the managed-rules file. Adding a new ID requires per-incident justification from the requester (example: an incident extending the baseline by one rule ID like `3ecd29ca…` should record *why* in the rule's inline comment). Do not invent.

